Question 5.1.7 (Dual Central Path):

Function: x*z

Constraint: P(a)*z = P(a)*c
             
Central Path: z(eta) in a set argmin{ x*z-sum_1_n[ln(z)] }

Primal vector: A*x=b

A proof why z(eta) = eta*/x(eta):

  The Central Path derivative with a weighted factor, argmin{ x*z-eta*sum_1_n[ln(z)]} = x - eta/z

                                                                                      = 0
    
                                                                                    z = x/eta 

A proof showing c'x(eta)-b*lambda(eta)=n*eta, where A*lambda = c-z(eta):

  The dual problem considers a second function and constraint at the current function's minimum or maximum.
 
  From Equation 5.47, P(a)*z = P(a)*c, so z = c. The Central Path funtion then becomes:

        argmin{ x*z-eta*sum_1_n[ln(z)] } = argmin{ x*c-eta*sum_1_n[ln(z)] }

  Added, the dual problem's constraint is argmin {b*lambda} = 0 for the exact equation:

        argmin{ x*c-eta*sum_1_n[ln(z)] } = argmin{ b*lambda }

  As the rearrangement shows from the earlier proof:

        c*x - b*lambda = eta*sum_1_n[ln(z)]

                       = eta*sum_1_n[ln(x/eta)]

                       = eta*n

                       when (x/eta)>>1, much greater than 1

                                              

        

